data.text:
Lukas Moodysson cites "The Chekist" by Russian film director Aleksandr Rogizhkin as an essential choice on his list of the greatest films ever made. This is a peculiar selection, although my opinion is no judgement on the film's relative quality. It is a strange pick given Moodysson's forestalling of allowing himself to engage fully with it. He was unable to stay awake during the screening at the Gothenburg Film Festival when he was first introduced to the work. Moodysson spoke about the film circa 2003 with a frank admission: ‘I hated it when I saw it 10 years ago, but it got stuck in me and refused to leave me. Now it's one of my favourites. I wish my own films to have the same effect, to live inside the viewer, like a virus.’ Perhaps Moodysson returned to the film and saw it in complete form, one might propose, but in fact he claims to have never revisited the missing pieces. Rather he allowed the incipient recollections of what little he did see aggregate in his memory, and that type of increased mental elevation may not withstand the realism attached to a physical replay, which might decimate the fragile staying power built up in his mind. His third feature film "Lilja 4-Ever" (known internationally as "Lilya 4-Ever") definitively obeys Moodysson's wish to live inside the viewer like a virus, for those who manage to endure the entire bleak, harrowing, tragic story played out under the director's uncompromising, unflinching watch. For those viewers who find the material too upsetting and can only bear to experience, say, the first fifteen minutes, will carry those pieces of the film with them even if that portion represents a fragmentary amoeba of the punishment still to be inflicted upon a teenage girl, as deliverance from a personal hell with a fragment of clemency persistently eludes her.

Thinking over my own list of definitive film experiences, I have noticed a pattern emerging, whereby a large minority of these titles were elevated to my personal canon only once I began a relationship of longevity with them in contemplation. Most movies produced with a desire for immediate financial riches tend to dissolve from our consciousness as quickly as the ephemera cinema ticket is disposed of after the showing. How can a filmmaker apply a stubborn viral entity into the balm of their art successfully? Not all of Moodysson's parasitic art can be defended as great, with his most shockingly disturbing feature "A Hole in My Heart" a glaring case in point. That film, I predict, will still be waiting for a reassessment of its redeeming qualities in perpetuity, because behind the disgusting, offensive content there is very little to recommend (though certain hardcore fans are stubbornly adamant that it deserves reappraisal). Perhaps that conveyor belt of extreme material was a consequentially provoked by the widespread critical acclaim bestowed upon "Lilya 4-Ever" and the recognition from Amnesty International and UNICEF as to urgency of the film's socio-political message, or even by the fact the film was quickly added to the curriculum in some Swedish schools - Moodysson did not even want "A Hole in My Heart" to be available outside of its theatrical release, specifically so children would be unable to view the material. As a few commentators have mentioned, actual pornography is likely more culturally valuable than that film. With "Lilya 4-Ever" Moodysson did not set out to make a film about disadvantaged communities, or to make a political statement on the human trafficking epidemic. He certainly is not lecturing us in the film, and attempting to assemble a feature film for education based study. It is simply a documentary styled drama about a single young female, and how the decisions made for her lead her down the path to the sex-slave industry. It is not until the final credits roll and a damning intertitle flashes before us to reveal just how common such a story is all around the world. Moodysson screened the film for some prostitutes and the feedback provided to him indicated that his story did not depict the very worst scenarios imaginable.

In reconsidering "Lilya 4-Ever" I was instantly struck by its powerful skill of insinuation, advocating restraint with suggestive properties. (Unlike "A Hole in My Heart," which included such graphic images for shock value, seemingly designed to test the resolve of a viewer's queasy stomach.) Much of the most painful suffering forced upon poor Lilya is mercifully experienced off-screen. This is not an evasion of a filmmaker's duty, but testament to Moodysson's confidence in his viewers to imagine the sadistic crimes for themselves because they, hopefully, will identify with the protagonist even if they cannot relate to her terminal misery. I could not for one moment concede that I know how this girl feels, as she exists in an environment so alien that it might as well be a different planet. The title card gives the first clue as it informs us that the film's events are taking place somewhere in the depleted remains of what was once the Soviet Union. The esteemed film critic Stephen Holden refers to this impoverished town ‘whose decrepit public housing resembles stacked-up rows of army barracks crumbling under a slate sky.’ Sean Axmaker, another film analyst, notes ‘the decaying blocks and abandoned submarine base of an economically deceased factory town.’ One gets the impression swiftly as Moodysson presents sweeping images over the opening intertitles of endless high-rises in low saturated colours, with a gloomy sky above threatening inclement weather. This place is a dead-end, and for all of its residents an escape is the only option from economic hardship and lifestyle boredom. It is no coincidence that the only luxurious venue in this wasteland is a loud, colourful nightclub, because below its prominent veil of pleasures is an underbelly of predatory entrapments from sinful characters robbing an innocent. They are easy prey because of their meagre alternative opportunities, with sniffing glue being the only escape option for those who wish to remain living.

This sense of lonely desperation is made utterly palpable right from the first scene commencing. A handheld camera travels along a pavement at a furious speed, while Rammstein's 'Mein Herz Brennt' wallops our eardrums at a raucous decibel level. Anthony Lane predicated in his review that the band's lead singer ‘hurls the words as if they were thunderbolts,’ and ‘if the god Wotan got caught in an overhead power cable, this is what he would sound like.’ It brings a seriousness and transcendence to the startling images. Next we catch glimpses of the teenage Lilya (Oksana Akinshina) running around this dreary urban landscape in a state of distress, with Moodysson's adoption of the handheld aesthetic increasing the chaotic urgency - an influential feature of that decade's incorporation of lightweight digital cameras. We have no idea why she is running, but the heavy metal musical counterpart can be interpreted as the high anxiety and paranoid restlessness caused by a juvenile's imbalanced hormones. Spliced within the hectic abrasive sights and sounds is a metaphorical illustration of the girl's fight for survival in a harsh world; a plume of thick smoke rising high from a factory as an isolated bird strives to circumvent the adulterating pollution. The opening segment concludes with Lilya on the verge of a motorway bridge overlooking incoming traffic below, with Moodysson intercuts long shots and close-ups of this human silently contemplating a suicide attempt with glazed eyes and pursed lips. Lilya's face is bruised and battered, and her awkward motion when run hints to further injuries on her lower body. This overture will be replayed by the film's conclusion, and when the German singer is heard at that point, what the viewer has been subjected to in the intervening chronicle of events somehow makes the music not only tolerable, but nearly cathartic. Moodysson peppers in less drastic electronic sounds throughout the film, a mix of Dubstep and Eurodance, and though the heavy metal might complement the tone and art direction of the film, these latter inclusions are engineered in such a counterpoint manner as to be mocking Lilya's plight, for they are inevitably connected to the clubbing scene, which will stage a critical turning point in her quest for salvation.

For a few minutes everything seems proportionately upbeat, as Lilya tells her friend Natasha (Elina Benenson) about her family's upcoming emigration to the United States, unable to contain the genuine excitement as she yells ‘America! America!’ in the outdoor streets, which resemble a bombed-out wreck. Her enthusiasm attracts the attention of a younger preadolescent boy who has been playing basketball on a makeshift court, by throwing old crushed drinks can through a rusted hoop with no net. Although unknown to us presently, the friendship between Lilya and this boy Volodya (Artyom Bogucharsky) will be the only saving grace in the entire motion picture. This is a dead environment containing characters that are as extreme in their heartlessness they might as well have no soul remaining inside themselves. Yes, it is gathered how the townspeople lost all their jobs over the years as the Cold War went in favour of the Americans, and the U.S.S.R. collapsed and crumbled - this town is tangible evidence of the struggle to rebuild into 21 separate republics, and a newly transnational country divides between Europe and Asia. Nevertheless, the selfishness, bitterness and downright hateful characteristics of every hostile person in this story that comes into contact with Lilya and Volodya needs to be seen to be believed. Even Lilya's school teacher, who should be expected to exert a sense of tactful courtesy due to her employment contract, sarcastically tells Lilya she has a glorious future ahead of her when informing her of the test score she achieved. One can speculate whether the exam was on the downfall of the Soviet Union, which had continually emphasised the prospect of a glorious future for its citizens that would never come to fruition and the teacher's comments is a transmission of her unresolved frustrations.

Lilya is unfortunately emancipated by her mother (Lyubov Agapova), as she informs her daughter that she will be left behind, and at a later date she might be sent for to join her and the new boyfriend in the United States. The balance of lightness and darkness in her life tilts towards greater presence of the dark. Lilya is devastated by this shocking development, and there is a scene depicting her unpacking the belongings already packed, including her prized possession (a painting) that is hung back up on the wall. She kneels daily and prays before the image of a child being guided by an angel. It is an apt symbolic expression for the dearth of a spiritual presence in her own life, and she is wise enough to know it is likely an illusory concept. Despite reciting the Lord's Prayer regularly, Lilya is by no means a saint when conducting herself in public, with a tendency to become obnoxious and arrogant during converses with neighbours and the local grocery shop assistant. I suspect that much of the spectator's engagement with the film comes from this multi-faceted composite figure, rather than a one-note pure example of innocence, because a flawed human is relatable even when her situation is beyond the realm of finding a mirrored kinship. Moodysson's subjective point-of-view shots will put us vicariously in a position to experience inhumanity from her perspective, aiding our ability to empathise with Lilya from a deeper vantage point. Her youth must always be in the forefront of our perception (she is aged 15 or 16), and thus liable to a naiveté with constitutive dreaming of a better tomorrow with overnight remedies. I will assess one of the film's strongest scenes dramatically, but firstly it is inconceivable to not notice how a follow-up incident is eerily reminiscent of that devastating moment, but with the shoe now on the other foot in the dynamic. Faced with an abandonment of her own, Lilya is unable to reconcile her traumatic stressful past to a present tense with this pain subverted on the precipice of a hopeful new beginning.

Chaos prevails in an outpouring of overwhelming, overwrought emotions. Lilya sulks as her mother comes to say goodbye and she exits without a proper embrace from a very disappointed daughter. Axmaker asserts: ‘Though her world is grey and grim, Lilya is full of life and desperate for love, which is in even shorter supply than money and jobs.’ She might already know that her chances of joining her mother in the west are slim, as the viewer is almost certain after being privy to an intimate bedroom confession, confirming the mother's wish for a new life with just her and the new boyfriend. Lilya's real father is an absent figure in the narrative. Is the mother's disownment of a child inexcusable neglect? Moodysson never incorporates parallel editing to update us on the mother's life in the United States. In the audience's speculative pondering, she is either a reprehensible individual who should never have raised a child, or she has been duped by a new lover and been brainwashed to think her child is old enough to look after herself as a young adult. It is strange that the mother should never write or send money, leading to possible theories that the mother has found herself in an unpromising capacity in the Promised Land. In this devastating scene, the actress Akinshina is immense as the static camera tightly registers who minutely shifting facial expressions in a tense thirty seconds, before the impending velocity of her unleashing of deep-rooted fears. Moodysson's rendering of the moment is breathtaking and exhilarating: the embrace between mother and daughter rings true, underlining the dubious actions of the former. Lilya's blue nightgown, in a way, echoes a prisoner of war inhabitant being eliminated from the family, and her slow motion descent into a patch of mud is suggestive of how little she is now worth in an environment without love or any commodities - only a stray dog takes any notice of her torment. The costume choice, in my eyes, presents Lilya as a lot younger than her actual age, adding to the sense of woe. In his review, Lane basically summed up this celluloid achievement: ‘A quarter of an hour ago, we had never encountered this girl and if we had been told her story, we would have filed it away as another dismal statistic.’ Is the scene too powerful to be accurately recorded? While "Lilya 4-Ever" has the appearance of a documentary style, there are forays into fantastic elements. This could be a subjective chronicling from inside Lilya's mind, replaying what actually happened but with an increased intensity towards a mother's pledge to keep in touch, when in reality she may have really driven off indifferently to an unwanted child's howls of anguish.

Lilya represses the ordeal as best she can. As scholar Anca Parvulesca addresses, ‘this section now unfolds in the temporal gap between the mother's departure and the promise of family reunification.’ She protests the command of her aunt (Lilya Shinkaryova) to move into a dismal flat, which looks as if the previous tenant died in it and he wasn't discovered for many weeks and nobody cleaned up after, but begrudgingly agrees to obey her relative's order. She hosts parties at home with some friends, and joins Natasha on a night out at a club. Wearing heavy make-up and long hair extensions, Lilya views the recreational activity as a source of fun to escape from her problems circling inwards. Natasha, however, sees it as an opportunity to earn money by agreeing to go off with a man in the club to reciprocate sexual favours. While left at the table waiting for her friend to return, Lilya is approached by a sleazy older man herself, and rejects his advances for paid sex. Lilya harbours the hope that one day her mother will announce her departure date to America. Both the best friend and the guardian aunt manipulate and take advantage of Lilya. Natasha, fearing for her own home comforts, spreads the rumour that it is Lilya who is the wannabe prostitute of the neighbourhood, and the aunt unceremoniously lies about being unable to afford her previous tenement. Lane brandishes her as ‘a raddled witch in a baseball cap’ who takes the large apartment all for herself showing no remorse for the deception. When social services summon Lilya to declare her mother's full neglect of responsibilities, it is a maddening conversation, the worker chalking it up to an unfortunate reversal fortune of the 'that's life' variety rather than a pledge to bring ownership to the mother's conduct and concern for the child's welfare immediately. When Lilya tells her aunt she has no food, no electricity, and no amenities other than the stash of glue comprising Volodya's sole commodity, her nonchalant response is to go spread her legs for paying clients.

By this point in the film, Volodya (Lane likens his appearance to that of ‘a Dickensian scrap of a boy’) has come to terms with the reality that his crush on Lilya is futile. Although a likeable character, he does feign a suicide attempt as a sneaky ploy to receive a kiss from Lilya, but admirably does demonstrate sincere guilt for this action. They bond closer, sharing little pieces of information about themselves - Lilya says she was born on the same day as Britney Spears, although not in the same year, and Volodya's musing that she could be accidentally mistaken for the pop singer is a potent reminder of the class structure inequity that people inherit. There are two emotionally impactful moments in this Act of the film that are not mentioned enough in reviews. After Lilya takes the aunt's advice, puking up her disgust afterwards, she goes to the grocery store and fills up her basket without caring about price tags. She looks over at the cashier with a haunting smile, as if envisaging the clerk's surprise that she can afford all these items. The deteriorated standard she previously set of discarding sinful money is gauged by the viewer. The second punch to the gut shows the composite nature of this protagonist even now. She uses some of the money to buy Volodya an actual basketball. When he opens his eyes to receive the gift, his vocal reaction goes beyond bashfulness. He is completely humbled by the present, prepared for Lilya to laugh and tell him that it isn't really his. The knowledge that a simple item like a basketball is a luxury in this corner of the world really hits home as he informs his friend he has never received any possession as nice. In other words, he never received anything on his day of birth from an abusive father. To us it is merely a ball, but notice how Volodya treasures the item long after it has been malevolently punctured - an analogy for deflated dreams.

Outside of the elated 'high' moments inhaling glue and jumping around with careless abandon at the desolate submarine base, their tender friendship is all that keeps both of them in a stable mindset. That location exists as a time capsule of Soviet posters and speeches proclaiming the prosperity for the next generation of citizens, which Lilya and Volodya belong to, and now they wander this dilapidated eyesore of post-communism (all it needs is the reappearance of a stray dog to resemble the Zone in Tarkovsky's "Stalker"). It may have been the site of Lilya's conception since her mother worked there when the man who contributed sperm passed through. Then, Moodysson brings us Andrei as a lifeline, a twenty-something man with a job, a car, and a surprisingly compassionate concern for Lilya. Rather than desiring her body, he wants to befriend her by going on a date to an amusement arcade. For a brief period, the organic smile radiating from Lilya momentarily allows us to forget where Andrei was first witnessed in the film. James Berardinelli posits how ‘Moodysson does an incomparable job of bonding the viewer with Lilya, so we see the world through her eyes.’ He continues by remarking how Lilya might share the viewer's anxiety that Andrei is too good to be true, ‘but the need to hope, believe, and dream is so sweet that she deceives herself.’ Volodya's opinions are thus diminished to that of snide comments formed out of jealousy towards a new protector. Moodysson doesn't literally show his hand of cards but it can be inferred from the precise location of Lilya and Andrei's first kiss. It takes place at an arcade machine mimicking an instrument of death - the electric chair, while Alphaville's 'Forever Young' colours the scene. Or maybe that facsimile should read: 4-ever young.

She has bonded strongly to him due to Andrei's grooming tactics, and thus he can easily invoke powers of persuasion to entice her move to Sweden. Andrei looks at Lilya seated next to him in the car, her smiled beaming with delight at his guarantee of her employment in Sweden, and Moodysson captures an interesting expression. He is unable to maintain contact with her jubilance, as if picturing her face once she arrives in Sweden and discovers that her living conditions will be even more penal (a trace of guilt in his complicity?). Volodya cannot cope alone in her absence, and Lilya cannot relinquish the fantasy to save her friend. Peter Bradshaw openly asks in his review if Lilya somehow deserves this fate for abandoning Volodya as her mother did, but nobody would wish such a fate on a young girl. The following sequences occurring in Moodysson's home country are a loose rumination on the true story of Danguolė Rasalaitė who was sold as a sex-slave in Malmö, after being abandoned by her own mother. When the film was shown in schools, research was undertaken to assess the reaction of the students to the rape representations. Critic Anthony Quinn describes these actions: ‘Close-ups of pale men, faces sweaty and contorted, loom horribly over the lens,’ and are juxtaposed ‘into a long, grotesque montage.’ Female pupils tended to empathise with the subject of the constricted point-of-view shot, which places them in alignment with what Lilya can see, trapped in her lack of freedom. Fewer males in the classroom were able to transmit their own self to the protagonist, and notice the camera's viewpoint expression.

The males primarily focused their response upon the humorous grunting sounds coming from the immoral rapists. Perhaps the images are so vile that such a reaction was needed to lighten the mood and to think that it's only a movie - many of these observers inexperienced in that form of intimacy could have their positive preconceptions crushed by this extremely vulgar depiction. Moodysson is very eager to avoid sexualising Lilya; when forced to play the role of the school girl with a perverted father, the attention is directed towards the absurd fetishist procedure, with Lilya's ridiculing undercutting of his role-playing dialogue earning our applause. These men will argue they have paid good money to have their way with her, but all that money goes to the pimp Sergei (Tonu Kark). As Lilya does not speak Swedish, and Sergei cannot understand Russian, his threats towards his 'cash cow' property are in broken English, explaining how he will kill Lilya if she tries to escape. Brinton Tench Coxe wrote insightfully about this aesthetically beautiful film's handling of generic expectations in its treatment of human trafficking and forced prostitution brutality. She asserts: ‘In this way, the film works against its own mode of cinematic production to liberate Lilya from any kind of scopophilic pleasure that might be enjoyed by the audience: Lilya and her body alternately perform both against and along with the mechanism of the film to resist being subordinated to celluloid as mere visual objects.’

I agree with certain constructive commentaries from dissenters, laying bare the flaws other critics cannot overlook in their muted praising evaluation. Parvulesca, for instance, raises the most common of criticisms: ‘Moodysson's script is explicitly didactic in amassing all possible arguments that might persuade Lilya that the dream of Sweden is worth pursuing.’ This is aided by the fact a ham-fisted Moodysson thoroughly created surrounding characters that have no goodness left to share in their hearts. Andrei ignites her burning desire for a Swedish land of complete contrast, devoid of evilness - her luck was in attracting and securing a boyfriend ‘equipped with the accoutrements that signify the promise of transnational upward mobility.’ Parvulesca cites further issues, stating that ‘Andrei's argumentation skills are poor, and Lilya is excessively naive.’ When Andrei tells Lilya he must visit his terminally ill grandmother before flying over himself, I do not think there is a viewer left with enough gullibility to accept his words at face value anymore. Earlier when Volodya precociously declared that vegetables cannot grow in winter and this pseudo-employment tease is all a ruse, Lilya lets her heart rule by admitting neither of them are experts on the Swedish climate. I am in favour of the film's climax, where Lilya has given up her search for love anywhere and refuses to remain enslaved. Without a passport she exists as a lost identity in a foreign land; a teenage girl could not grasp how police would treat her if she went to them for a reprieve. Even if Volodya could offer her the world as an angel presence, Parvulesca opines ‘that there are no available routes for someone like Lilya in Europe,’ as she stares down at the open road below her on this indifferent highway bridge, knowing there is no survival to her reality journey, only an end destination.

Lukas Moodysson has never been able to top his 2002 feature which, alongside the brave and touching lesbian story "Show Me Love" (1998) and the understated satirical humour found inside a commune in "Together" (2000), seemed to herald the beginnings of a new, great Scandinavian hope post-Bergman with exquisite versatility. In recent times his cinematic output has dried up as other artistic and creative mediums have taken precedence, but no matter whether he returns with another great movie, this early triumvirate has sealed his place as a borderline candidate in a hypothetical Hall of Fame for filmmakers. The title of "Lilya 4-Ever" deserves some final introspection. Yes, I can argue that it reinforces the idea of the film as a viral invader, depositing itself inside the viewer's psyche forever more. The title is precisely the phrase she inscribes onto a public bench, determined to finish every symbol despite the barrage of humiliating taunts from degenerate onlookers. Volodya visits her as an impressionable guardian angel, telling his friend that you have all of eternity to be dead, but only a small window to be amongst the living. He uses her graffiti as an analogy: she wouldn't leave when he asked because she wanted to finish things on her own terms and not give up. Despite all the inhumane restrictions placed on her freedom, Lilya remains an active agent of an authentic woman, giving a human face and voice to millions of faceless, voiceless victims globally. I leave the ultimate verbiage of defiance to this victimised individual in response to a rapist: ‘I'm not your property. Think you can buy me? You can't buy me. You can't buy my heart and soul.’
